<DOC><DOCNO> AP880822-0089 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-22-88 1236EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Nobels     08-22 0320</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Nobels,0332</SECOND><HEAD>Dates Set For Announcement of Nobel Prizes</HEAD><DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Nobel Foundation said Monday thatthe 1988 Nobel Peace Prize winner will be announced Sept. 29.   President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachevreportedly are among the top contenders for the richest Nobel awardever.   The prize for medicine will be awarded Oct. 17, for economy onOct. 18 and the prizes for physics and chemistry on Oct. 19, theNobel Foundation said.   By tradition, the date for awarding the literature prize is keptsecret until one week before the announcement.   Each Nobel laureate will receive about $385,000, which is about15 percent higher than last year.   The Peace prize announcement will be made in Oslo, Norway, bythe Nobel Committee of the Norwegian parliament. The others will beannounced in Stockholm by the Swedish Acedemy of Sciences, theKarolinska Institute of medicine, and by the prestigious 18-memberliterary committee known as the Swedish Academy.   The prizes will be distributed Dec. 10 in Oslo and Stockholm.   The Norwegian press has reported that Reagan and Gorbachev werenominated for signing a treaty to dismantle their medium- andshorter-range nuclear missiles.   The Nobel committee refuses to confirm the names of thecandidates, whose nominations had to be submitted before Feb. 1.   A Norwegian member of parliament has said he nominated PresidentCorazon Aquino of the Philippines, and five Swedishparliamentarians announced they had proposed a campaigner againstthe death penalty in the United States, the Rev. Joseph Ingle ofthe Nashville, Tenn.-based Southern Coalition on Jails and Prisons.   Other possible nominations include Pope John Paul II, jailedSouth African black leader Nelson Mandela, Indian Prime MinisterRajiv Gandhi and Mordechai Vanunu, an Israeli imprisoned on treasoncharges for disclosing details of his country's nuclear capability.   Costa Rican President Oscar Arias won the 1987 Peace prize fordrafting a plan to end the fighting in Central America.</TEXT></DOC>